I am not a big "burger" person--- which is the reason why it took me so long to try this place. I went there yesterday: It is FANTASTIC. I had a BLT, my favorite sandwich, made with hormone-free bacon, organic veggies and some deliciously toasted white bread. (I know, I know, I should have gotten the whole grain.) This place aims HIGH. I mean, really HIGH. There is quality everywhere and the staff is about the friendliest I have seen in the neighborhood, which is Park Slope, Brooklyn.  So come: Prepare to be dazzled. I your aim is for dinner, I suggest the sunset before the weather gets too cold. There is a patio.  There is organic wine. There are great beers on tap.  So, Dear Reader, you must understand: I plied my trade as a newspaper reporter for quite a long while.  I learned, during my visit, that Burger Village, now in its fourth year of operation, is owned by Indians. That would be folk from South East Asia.  This makes the most sense to me: They have a profound respect for what we put into our bodies.  Hat's off to Burger Village! And when I do have my one burger this year, it will be here! --- Karen Donovan

Burger Village has fast become my family's favorite burger spot! Their selection of meats such as ostrich, elk, boar, etcetera, as well as the vegan, "Impossible Burger" are all wonderful and accompanied by a wide range of topping options that are suitable for virtually all tastes. In addition to that, they have a nice selection of craft beers, milkshakes and salads. Their sides are limited but what they have (Onion Rings, Fries, Sweet Potato Fries) are quality and don't disappoint. Lastly, we have been to two Burger Village locations, multiple times and have never had service that was anything other than terrific!

Burger Village is the first burger joint I've ever visited that has a menu that can satisfy both meat-eaters and vegans alike.  This location used to be Cheeburger Cheeburger, a strictly meat-only establishment.  I'm sure that due to this new restaurant being in Park Slope full of educated people with vastly different nutritional lifestyles, serving burgers with meat and non-meat options was a smart move to corner both markets.  My son ordered a beef burger; I ordered the Impossible Burger, a vegan burger that tasted amazingly meat-like.  For the vegans out there, there were five vegan burger options to choose from.  Pretty much everything in this place is organic including the bottles of ketchup and mustard that were standing at each table.  There are eight different salads to choose from, but we didn't order any salads during our visit.  The fresh-cut fries that my son ordered were delicious.  I ordered a bottle of locally-made kombucha that tasted better than most other brands I've tried.  There was a good vibe in this place full of happy workers.  By the time the dessert menu came, I was too stuffed to order.  I would definitely come back to this place to order the same food again, or maybe try another vegan burger option from their menu even though I can still salivate for another Impossible Burger.

Ugh.  Juice press had no soup and I had my infant son with me so was trying to keep it super healthy/organic.  I decided to try this place.  It smelled of grease - the kind that sticks to your clothes and your hair until you take a shower and wash your clothes.  I had the black bean burger based on the servers rec and it was seriously disgusting.  It tasted like freezer burn nothingness.  I have been vegetarian for over a decade and have had many a variety of veggie burger.  This was seriously one of the worst.  I also had the minestrone soup which was also awful, thin, and pretty tasteless.  It was seriously one of the worst meals I have had in years.  The waitress was also extremely stressed out despite there being like 2 other tables, and made me feel very rushed and nervous and I didn't want to ask for anything extra or that would take her time.  Idk maybe if you order meat it's another story but I would never, ever, ever go to this place again.  Organic food most definitely doesn't have to taste like this!!!

Discovered this place a week ago and have been there twice already. The way they set up the ingredients is really clever and unique. If not from nyc, it may be pricier than usual for a burger but for here it’s the average price for a restaurant. Had the bison burger with retro era on multigrain bread and then bison burger - again - and retro era with extra of avocado. Side of seasoned French fries. Will go again and again here! IG: @tutieats
